[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(57) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "A rich man of Arimathæa.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The place so named was probably identical with the Ramah of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 1:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the birth-place of the prophet. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the name is given in its uncontracted form as Ramathaim-zophim, and in the LXX. version it appears throughout as Armathaim, in Josephus as Armatha, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Maccabees 11:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as Ramathem. It was a city of the Jews, in the narrower sense in which that word meant the people of Judæa (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 23:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The site is more or less conjectural, but if we identify the Ramah, or Ramathaim, of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with the modern ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Nebby Samuel,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " about four miles north-west of Jerusalem, we have a position which sufficiently fits in with the circumstances of the history. Of Joseph we are told by St. Mark (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 15:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") that he was “an honourable counsellor,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a member of the Sanhedrin, and that he was looking for the kingdom of God; by St. Luke (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 23:50-51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), that he was “a good man, and a just” (see Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 5:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for the distinction between the two words); by St. John ( ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), that he was “a disciple, but secretly for fear of the Jews.” He was apparently a man of the same class and type of character as Nicodemus, respecting our Lord as a man, admiring Him as a teacher, half-believing in Him as the Christ, and yet, till now, shrinking from confessing Him before men. For us the name has the interest of being one of the few New Testament names connected with our own country. He was sent, it was said, by Philip (the Apostle) to Britain. There, in the legend which mediæval chroniclers delighted to tell, he founded the Church of Glastonbury; and the staff which he stuck into the ground took root and brought forth leaves and flowers, and became the parent of all the Glastonbury thorns from that day to this. We have to place the piercing of the side, narrated by St. John only (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:31-37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), before Joseph’s application.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "27:57-61 In the burial of Christ was nothing of pomp or solemnity. As Christ had not a house of his own, wherein to lay his head, while he lived, so he had not a grave of his own, wherein to lay his body, when he was dead. Our Lord Jesus, who had no sin of his own, had no grave of his own. The Jews designed that he should have made his grave with the wicked, should have been buried with the thieves with whom he was crucified, but God overruled it, so that he should make it with the rich in his death, Isa 53:9. And although to the eye of man the beholding a funeral may cause terror, yet if we remember how Christ by his burial has changed the nature of the grave to believers, it should make us rejoice. And we are ever to imitate Christ's burial in being continually occupied in the spiritual burial of our sins.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "When the even was come - That is, some time after three o'clock in the afternoon. Before this, the Jews had besought Pilate that the legs of those who were crucified might be broken and the bodies be taken down, that they might not remain on the cross during the Sabbath. The soldiers, coming to Jesus for that purpose, found that he was already dead, contrary to their expectation. A soldier, however, thrust a spear into his side, and there was furnished the fullest proof that he had expired. See the notes at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:31-37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A rich man of Arimathea - It is uncertain where Arimathea was. There were several cities of that name in Judea. It is commonly supposed to be the same as Rama. See the notes at Matthew 2:17. Luke says that this was a \"city of the Jews,\" and it is probable, therefore, that it was in the tribe of Benjamin, and but a short distance from Jerusalem. This man sustained a high character. He was an \"honorable counsellor, who also waited for the kingdom of God\" Mark 15:43; he was \"a good man and a just\" Luke 23:50; he had nobly set himself against the wicked purposes of the Sanhedrin Luke 23:51; he was a disciple of Jesus, though he was not openly his follower, because he feared the Jews, John 19:38. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "A rich man of Arimathea - It is uncertain where Arimathea was. There were several cities of that name in Judea. It is commonly supposed to be the same as Rama. See the notes at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 2:17",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Luke says that this was a \"city of the Jews,\" and it is probable, therefore, that it was in the tribe of Benjamin, and but a short distance from Jerusalem. This man sustained a high character. He was an \"honorable counsellor, who also waited for the kingdom of God\" ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Mark 15:43",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; he was \"a good man and a just\" ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 23:50",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; he had nobly set himself against the wicked purposes of the Sanhedrin ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 23:51",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; he was a disciple of Jesus, though he was not openly his follower, because he feared the Jews, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 19:38",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
